<dl id="n10139d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10139d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10139d"> 139(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> wants his calico back <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10139d"><li>FW 516.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n10139d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n10139d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10139d">MS BL 47482b-113</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:085 <a name="rA2yyd" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rA2yyd">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA2yyd.htm#n10139d">Draft: III&sect;3A.2++</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">But there is worse to come. Take another vile expedient having the same sad objective, I mean, the swelling of this Westward-going stream of slavery: the &ldquo;Shylock system&rdquo; among the natives. Here is the trader&apos;s chance, and the borrowing native is soon involved in a quagmire of trouble, to wit, a 1000 per cent extortion on the borrowed goods. (Not an E.O.E. invoice, by any means, for this arrogant Shylock never makes an error and never omits anything.) Snr. &mdash;&mdash; is a case in point: As usual, he does not <mark>want his calico back</mark>, he wants payment, not in cash but in kind, and that kind the best kind, yea, the human kind. <small> Daniel Crawford, <a name="DCTB" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DCTB"><cite title="source">Thinking Black</cite></a> (1912) 46-7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Calico: plain white unprinted cotton cloth. </mm> </dd></dl>
